node.text:
Explorer/Activist Johan Ernst Nilson. Nilson has climbed the Seven Summits (and many other peaks), visited 178 countries and some of the most remote places on Earth, and he is in the Guinness Book of World Records for his Three Poles Challenge Expedition. His travels and experiences have allowed him to see climate change and its consequences first hand, and now Nilson is an activist for change, leading people on expeditions, giving talks, and making films about the environment.

The Astronomia Everest project started with renowned Swedish explorer and environmental activist @johanernst taking an Astronomia Tourbillon with him on an expedition to the Himalayas.
"I wore the regular Astronomia Tourbillon on my last climb to the Himalayas, where I went up to 6,200 meters (almost 20,000 feet), in -30 C degree, extreme conditions," Nilson says. "You would think that such a complicated watch would be delicate and fragile, but it isn't, and it performed perfectly in all conditions. I used it climbing up ice walls, with my ice ax, banging it against rock and ice and it held up extremely well.”

Explorer/Activist Johan Ernst Nilson. Nilson has climbed the Seven Summits (and many other peaks), visited 178 countries and some of the most remote places on Earth, and he is in the Guinness Book of World Records for his Three Poles Challenge Expedition. His travels and experiences have allowed him to see climate change and its consequences first hand, and now Nilson is an activist for change, leading people on expeditions, giving talks, and making films about the environment.

node.text:
Push the right-hand crown of the incredible BUGATTI Chiron Tourbillon and the engine comes to life – the crankshaft turns and the 16 pistons pump up and down, just like BUGATTI’S iconic W16 engine. Two “turbochargers” on the side of the engine block spin while the engine runs, adding to the visual impact.
Incredible to see and unbelievably complicated to realize (the movement is comprised of 578 components), the BUGATTI Chiron Tourbillon timepiece seamlessly marries engines and watches – something no other watchmaker has done before.

The Astronomia Everest project started with renowned Swedish explorer and environmental activist @johanernst taking an Astronomia Tourbillon with him on an expedition to the Himalayas.
"I wore the regular Astronomia Tourbillon on my last climb to the Himalayas, where I went up to 6,200 meters (almost 20,000 feet), in -30 C degree, extreme conditions," Nilson says. "You would think that such a complicated watch would be delicate and fragile, but it isn't, and it performed perfectly in all conditions. I used it climbing up ice walls, with my ice ax, banging it against rock and ice and it held up extremely well.”

Explorer/Activist Johan Ernst Nilson. Nilson has climbed the Seven Summits (and many other peaks), visited 178 countries and some of the most remote places on Earth, and he is in the Guinness Book of World Records for his Three Poles Challenge Expedition. His travels and experiences have allowed him to see climate change and its consequences first hand, and now Nilson is an activist for change, leading people on expeditions, giving talks, and making films about the environment.

In the world of watchmaking, the presence of a tourbillon in a watch’s movement places the piece among the elite. @JacobandCo’s Twin Turbo Furious 300+ sets itself apart from this rarified group, incorporating two accelerated triple axis tourbillons into its striking design. The tourbillons work to compensate for the effects of gravity on the precision of the movement.⠀ ⠀
⠀
Even the case of the Twin Turbo Furious Bugatti 300+ is super complicated – made of forged carbon, with a titanium core to ensure water resistance - the case alone is comprised of 88 parts. The grand complication movement is made up of 832 individual parts – incredible to consider that many parts coming together, and amazing to see in action.⠀

node.text:
A candy-colored rainbow of gems cover the Brilliant Flying Tourbillon Peru Mountain III. A total of 146 baguette-shaped multicolored sapphires (12.22 total carats) are invisibly set on the dial in shades of red, blue, yellow and green. Not to be left out, the crown is surrounded by 14 baguette-shaped multicolored sapphires and topped with a 1.06-carat cabochon sapphire. The dial is further enhanced with a one-minute flying tourbillon at 6 o’clock. 
The gems are housed in a 47mm 18k rose gold case. 

The one-of-a-kind jewelry timepiece is powered by the manually wound Jacob & Co. Caliber JCBM01a with an impressive 100-hour power reserve. The sapphire glass caseback provides a proper view of the movement’s bridges which are paved with 346 brilliant-cut diamonds and a gadroon power reserve indicator set with eight baguette rubies and pink sapphires.

The 47mm case of the Epic X Chrono Black and White is made of Black DLC Grade 5 titanium and White ceramic.

Smoked sapphire glass is used for the dial and caseback. Dial finishes include black satin anodized aluminum inner rings and subdial rings. The Epic X Black Titanium and Green is powered by the JCAA05 automatic semi-skeletonized high-end column-wheel chronograph movement made up of 260 components. The movement with its bi-compax design is partially revealed through a smoked sapphire glass dial and caseback.

There’s a small seconds indicator at 9 o’clock, a minute counter at 3 o’clock, rotating inner bezel ring timer controlled by a crown at 10 o’clock, and a red central chronograph seconds hand.

The Epic X Tourbillon Khabib is powered by the Jacob & Co. JCAM03 manually wound skeleton tourbillon, which operates the timing functions and a vertically angled tourbillon balance wheel with a 72-hour power reserve. The skeletonized movement provides a view of the watch’s mechanics. 

The highly versatile sports watch is completed with a black rubber or Cordura strap, with a titanium and black PVD buckle.

node.text:
Jacob and company watchmakers carefully assemble the Epic X Tourbillon Khabib before sending it out the world. The final details are many and includes securing the bridge and hands of the skeletonized movement. Then they ensure that the tourbillon and exposed balance spring are in sync before securing the sapphire crystal and titanium case. Finally, the caseback is placed on the watch with the sketch of Khabib and his 29-0 UFC record etched into the sapphire crystal case.

node.text:
The relationship between Ultimate Fighting Champ. Khabib, and Jacob Arabo, the founder of Jacob & Co., is based on mutual respect and admiration. Khabib retired from the Octagon with the winningest record of all time, a perfect 29-0, and Jacob is one of the world’s most famous jewelers and watchmakers.

Together they created a collection of limited-edition watches. The Epic X Khabib series has features related to his exceptional UFC career. His 29-0 record, his nickname “The Eagle,” engraving, and his iconic Papakha hat engraved on the sapphire caseback are among the details on this epic timepiece.

A pair of interchangeable platinum Cluster earrings features 12 pear-shaped diamonds and four marquis-cut diamonds arranged in flower motifs totaling more than 38 carats. They can be worn as is or with a pair of impressive fancy brownish yellow pair shaped diamonds totaling more than 42 carats set in yellow gold. 

The Fancy Brownish Yellow diamonds are designed to dangle beneath the white diamond flower motif. Worn together they are rare combination of being understated, elegant and bold.

More than 23 carats of bright sparkling invisible-set, baguette-shaped, step-cut diamonds in in a classic boule shaped ring. 

A total of 88 gems with D - F color and VVS - VS clarity set in 18K white gold that is barely visible among the sparkling gems. As this ring shows, diamond sourcing and gem-setting are among the specialties of Jacob & Co.
